snippet.textDisplay:
Exposed as a CHECKBOOK MANAGER.

That wasn't very good, Pep. What rich club are you trying to manage next, Pep, now that City isn't attractive for you, with its FFP problems and a rebuild needed there? As I have been saying, there are great checkbook managers and there are great managers. Ranieri is a PROVEN great manager; Pep is a PROVEN checkbook manager. There is a big difference.

And Pep runs away as soon as there's trouble. He only hangs around when the going is good. He's a bit of a coward. Never wants to prove himself. You won't catch him take a job like West Ham, Bournemouth or Brighton, where he would have a chance to really prove himself.

He'd get found out and become a laughing stock.

Ranieri is different. He WILL go after the small jobs, and he's proven himself there. It wasn't just Leicester, it is also at Monaco and Fiorentina, he proved himself.

Took Monaco to second place the first year out of Ligue 2.

Took Fiorentina to fourth place the first year out of Serie B.

No one can do that except Ranieri.

When you know his history, you realize his winning the title with Leicester is not that astonishing. He has a pattern of excelling. He is a great manager. Period.

Anyone can win the league with a checkbook. How many can win the league with a small club? Very few people can.

Managing a small club is the REAL TEST, not managing a big club.

I don't even count Mourinho as proven. He won the UCL with Porto but winning the UCL with a small club can happen, and it does relatively frequently. Even Hamburg won the UCL; would you say Hamburg's manager is the greatest in the world? Of course not. Flukes happen and the UCL is a contest that can be won by luck.

Winning a league is a different ball game. You don't get lucky throughout the whole 38-game process (unless you're Liverpool and referee decisions always go your way - the latest one being the handball by Soyuncu that wasn't), so winning the league is the true TEST, and the so-called great managers like Pep, Mourinho, Ancelotti, Zidane are still not proven.

If Mourinho wins with Spurs next season (so long as Levy doesn't spend 300 million in one transfer window or something crazy like that), I will say he's proven.

If Ancelotti wins the league with Everton next season, say, spending <150 million, I would call him proven too.

But I don't call them proven winning major silverware with Real, Chelsea, Bayern and PSG.

Even at Inter, Mourinho didn't prove himself. He got top players to come to him and was given a huge check by Inter.

It can become a scam by these managers. They approach these clubs and say, "I won't work for you unless you guarantee me 300 million in spending in 2 years ..."

So of course they are going to keep up their winning reputation.

In fact, I'm being generous calling Spurs and Everton "tests". These managers have worked out a deal with the owners prior to signing. So we know they're going to be backed.

I'm just giving them leeway because these clubs haven't won big stuff for years so they got rusty about knowing how to win.
